@samguptawbsrocks @Walker Reynolds @zackscriven @sqlwalkermj I'm working at a stamping plant that has Infor ERP and a Rockware (not Rockwell) SCADA system to calculate OEE and visualize machine states. I can see the SCADA is an MS Access front end. The company's strategy is to consolidate as much as possible into the Infor ERP system. I'm there as a quality engineer and among other things, trying to collect more and better process data that is not being collected, as well as participating in the ERP upgrade to the latest version of Infor. My questions: 
1)    Have you seen Infor’s MES system (https://webassets.infor.com/resources/Brochures/Infor-MES.pdf) and think it would be an appropriate replacement for the MS Access based system?

2)    How would a platform like Ignition, FactoryStudio fit into the picture and move toward the UNS structure?

@DavidSchultz Not sure that a fully composable platform is all that close for MES if you're waiting for the current names in the space to do it. Getting a set of "building blocks" that can be used as a quasi-low code approach may look reasonably easy to do, but the customization of business logic is the part that makes every legacy MES product fail. (Along with the lack of a standard back end, it is also what will contribute to Tulip being unable to provide a good solution for Enterprise clients as well.)

@GeoffNunan and his team at Libre are in the process of taking the BPMN-based business logic (read as "custom MES process") editor and engine from Prototype to Product right now. It's a drag and drop UI on top of a crazy fast processing engine that interacts with the underlying Headless MES and Knowledge Graph. Once that is complete, Libre will be as close as you can get to a composable platform. The missing bit will be that Libre is UI agnostic and doesn't build MES apps. Fortunately, the UI is the least important part of the MES and since Libre is a single access point GraphQL API, apps are "easy" to compose.

Maybe composable for mfg is closer than I thought... 🤣

